<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
06/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   FED OFFICIALS APPEAR to have no intention of cutting
short-term interest rates, despite signs of a stagnant
economy. The officials seem convinced that last week's weak
employment report doesn't presage a recession. Furthermore,
they are concerned that their tight-money policies have so
far failed to head off an acceleration of inflation.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Tomkins of Britain agreed to acquire Philips Industries, a
maker of windows, bathtubs and other products, for $550
million. The deal follows the collapse of a buy-out of
Philips.
   ---
   National Intergroup's chairman agreed to step down next
year after the firm sells everything but its drug
distributor. Dissident holders expressed satisfaction, but
said the whole company should be liquidated.
   ---
   Sales of U.S.-built cars and light trucks fell 3.3% in
late May. But auto makers dismissed the possibility of huge
discounts at the end of the model year in September, because
stocks of unsold vehicles are relatively modest.
   ---
   Stock and bond prices declined as investors took profits
after two days of strong gains. The Dow Jones industrials
fell 10.19 points to 2925.00.
   ---
   The cable TV industry indicated it would accept a
reregulation of its basic rates, and limits on the size and
activities of major operators.
   ---
   Drexel is expected to present a proposed reorganization
plan to its creditors today that would pay them 100 cents on
the dollar.
   ---
   Saudi Arabia moved to damp speculation that it is
launching an oil-price war, after the kingdom's discount
plans triggered a petroleum sell-off.
   ---
   Businessland is forming a Japanese unit with Canon,
Fujitsu, Sony and Toshiba as investors. The move by the
biggest U.S. dealer of personal computers supplements a
similar push into Europe. But the Japanese PC market may
prove perilous.
   ---
   Equimark's Claire Gargalli quit as head of its main
banking unit amid speculation that the parent intends to put
itself up for sale. Equimark's chairman denied any sale
plans.
   ---
   Three Campbell Soup holders pooled most of their 17.4%
stake and called again for a sale of the firm. Campbell stock
jumped on the news.
   ---
   The Bush administration unveiled its plan to give the SEC
jurisdiction over stock-index futures. The proposal would
stiffen regulation of the products and also give the
government power to set margin requirements.
   ---
   Saatchi posted an $11.8 million fiscal first-half loss,
citing heavy debt, a British ad slowdown and consulting
losses. Separately, the firm agreed to sell Hay Group to the
consulting unit's management for $90 million.
   ---
   Limited antitrust liability for certain joint production
ventures was endorsed by the House. Triple damages would no
longer apply if the activities were disclosed to the
government.
   ---
   Greyhound Lines may be forced to make peace with its
striking drivers if it is to emerge successfully from Chapter
11, some creditors believe. They may demand such a
settlement.
   ---
   Increasing SEC power to gather Wall Street data was
approved by the House. The bill, which must be reconciled
with a Senate version, would also let the agency take steps
against program trading, a provision opposed by the Bush
administration.
   ---
   Coca-Cola Enterprises agreed to purchase a bottler in
Arkansas for $250 million and to sell bottling interests in
Ohio for $120 million.
   ---
   Adolph Coors agreed to buy its first brewery outside
Colorado from Stroh, giving the buyer its first large group
of union workers in 13 years.
   ---
   Paramount Communications posted a 67% drop in fiscal
secondquarter profit, but reversed its loss from continuing
operations.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 199,720,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2925.00, off 10.19; transportation 1212.59, up 4.74;
utilities 215.10, off 0.32.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3419.49, off
7.41.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.71, up 0.98; spot
index 132.99, up 0.53.
   Dollar: 152.45 yen, up 0.05; 1.6850 marks, off 0.0005.
</TEXT>
