<HL>
   Equimark Bank Unit Chairwoman Quits
   Amid Speculation Firm to Go on the Block
   ----
   By James S. Hirsch
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   EQK WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   PITTSBURGH -- The chairwoman of Equimark Corp.'s main
banking unit resigned amid increased speculation that the
parent company is preparing to put itself up for sale.
   The departure of Claire Gargalli, one of the nation's
highest-ranking woman bankers, as chairwoman of Equibank
comes one week after the resignation of another top
executive, Judith E. Fellheimer. The moves are part of a
cost-cutting program in which more than 20 middle and senior
managers have been fired, four Philadelphia branch banks have
been sold, and executive perks have been trimmed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The moves have prompted speculation that Equimark's
embattled chairman, Alan S. Fellheimer, who together with his
wife owns 13% of Equimark, is trying to trim the bank to make
it more attractive for sale. The departure of the bank unit's
two most senior executives has also fueled rumors that
Equibank may have unacknowledged problem loans. But in an
interview, Mr. Fellheimer vigorously denied that either the
company was for sale or that the executives were fired.
   Wall Street reacted favorably to the news as buyers bid up
the stock on takeover speculation. In New York Stock Exchange
composite trading, Equimark rose 75 cents to $8.625 in heavy
trading.
   For his part, Mr. Fellheimer insisted he has no plans to
sell the bank. He contends the recent cost-savings were made
necessary when Equimark's $116 million acquisition of
National Bancshares Corp. of Texas fell through. Equimark,
which has about $3.8 billion in assets, had added staff
assuming that the deal would come to fruition.
   Moreover, Mr. Fellheimer said, personnel cuts were needed
because the focus of the bank has changed. With earnings
down, Equimark won't be looking for acquisitions, which have
been a source of growth over the past several years.
   Even without diversions, the bank has plenty of problems
at home. The bank had a loss of $15.4 million in the first
quarter and is dogged by rumors that it will have to take
further write-offs this year to cover bad real estate loans,
particularly in the Philadelphia area.
   Mr. Fellheimer wouldn't comment on the possibility of more
write-offs or on earnings projections.
   The 57-year-old Ms. Gargalli said she walked away from her
job, which paid about $600,000 a year before bonuses, because
she agrees that the company had too many senior executives
for its current size. Her decision to leave clearly surprised
many at the bank. At one department meeting where the
announcement was made, employees gasped when they heard the
news.
   Ms. Gargalli, who will receive a severance package, said
the decision to leave Equimark was her own. She worked at the
bank unit since 1984 when federal regulators were threatening
to shut it down, and eventually became Equimark's No. 2
executive. She had held the top post since 1987, and will be
succeeded in that post by James McLaughlin, currently the
bank's president.
   Her departure leaves Mr. Fellheimer without two longtime
executives who were instrumental in helping to bring Equimark
back to financial health after he became chairman in 1985.
Nevertheless, he insisted that the changes were necessary.
"I'm doing everything I can to slim down" the company, he
said. "We had no sacred cows."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900606-0130
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900606-0130.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bethlehem Steel Might Trim Products,
   Examine Joint Ventures, Chairman Says
   ----
   By Clare Ansberry
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   BS LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp., still struggling with lackluster
performance at its major Pennsylvania operations, may
eventually have to scale back certain products.
   Chairman Walter F. Williams said the company remains
committed to its three Pennsylvania plants, despite their
continued lackluster performance. But the No. 2 steelmaker
may have to take "some other steps" in the future, he
acknowledges, such as changing the product mix at those
sites. He declined to elaborate.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Separately, while Bethlehem hasn't yet seen the need to
enter a major joint-venture agreement with a foreign
steelmaker, Mr. Williams said "this could change."
   He said Pennsylvania plants in Bethlehem, Steelton, and
Johnstown have made great strides in becoming more efficient
but continue to face tough minimill competition, excess
capacity and dwindling markets. He pointed out, for example,
that the market for heavy rail, which is made at Steelton, is
practically nonexistent.
   Moreover, minimills have concentrated on bar products,
which Bethlehem makes at its Johnstown plant, and are
increasingly looking to the Bethlehem's own Northeast
backyard to locate operations. In addition, structural
products, made at Bethlehem and used for building, have
suffered from the soft construction market.
   While Mr. Williams doesn't expect to undertake massive
capital programs at those operations, he said the company
would add enough capital to ensure "viable operations as time
goes by." He said all three provide "positive cash flow."
   The company could try to renegotiate a lower-cost labor
accord with the United Steelworkers of America for those
plants. Mr. Williams noted that the 50-month contract,
negotiated last year, recognized that certain operations
facing intense competition might require new contract terms.
"We have been doing some talking," with the union, he said.
   He said he doesn't expect any "big change," such as
closing plants in the near future. "We think we can still
hold our own" in structural, bar, and rail products, he said.
   Bethlehem's prize plants at Sparrows Point and Burns
Harbor, he said are "both very good and will be better." The
company is spending $200 million to modernize its hot-strip
mill at Sparrows Point and recently completed a $50 million
vacuum degassing facility at Burns Harbor.
   Bethlehem also plans to spend $300 million to build three
hot-dip coating lines to create corrosion-resistant sheets of
steel.
   Most other major steelmakers have entered into
joint-venture agreements with foreign steelmakers to build
new coating lines. Bethlehem hasn't to date but it "very
possibly could" at one of the new coating lines, Mr. Williams
said.
   "Up to now we haven't seen a fit," he said. He pointed out
that steelmakers typically form joint ventures to get cash or
technology, but Bethlehem has an untouched $500 million
revolving line of credit and already buys technology from
foreign companies.
   Mr. Williams declined to make a specific second-quarter
earnings projection, but said "we're still predicting that
the second half will be a little stronger and 1991 even
stronger than that." In the year-ago quarter, Bethlehem
earned $84.1 million, or $1.03 a share, on sales of $1.43
billion.
   Steelmakers in general don't expect this year's second
quarter to top the robust year-ago period, when the industry
was still enjoying the tail end of a two-year recovery.
Although prices and orders seem to be rising, most of the
improvements won't be felt until the second half.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900606-0129
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900606-0129.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   You Can Bet Someone Out There
   Is Already Scripting `Airport '90'
   ----
   By James S. Hirsch
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<LP>
   As urban problems go, groundhogs don't rank that high in
most places. In Columbus, Ohio, however, the fat, furry
creatures have overrun the airport, and the authorities there
want to take up arms -- literally -- against them.
   But turning prairie land next to the paved runways into a
sort of Wild West makes some people uneasy. The issue came to
a head Monday night, when the City Council voted on whether
to allow airport personnel to use firearms against several
thousand of the burrowing rodents.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The problem stems from a population explosion beneath the
grassy 180-acre field. Officials attribute the groundhogs'
fertility to a spate of warm winters.
   The plump creatures "don't hibernate as long as they did
in colder weather," says John Carpenter, operations officer
for the Port Authority International Airport. "They get bored
and have to do something, so they have more kids."
   And a mischievous lot they are. Among other things, they
burrow underground and gnaw on buried electrical cables. Mr.
Carpenter also fears a gamboling groundhog may collide with a
small aircraft and perhaps mangle the landing gear.
   Federal regulations being what they are, Mr. Carpenter
says the groundhogs cast a shadow over the future of the
airfield. Airport authorities have tried to kill the critters
by dropping cannisters of poison gas into burrows and setting
traps above ground.
   "Somone suggested mothballs, but with 180 acres, you're
talking about a lot of mothballs," Mr. Carpenter says.
   Desperate, officials asked the city if the airport could
arm several maintenance employees with shotguns and so-called
varmint slugs, which have a hollow point and spread out upon
impact, thus tending to kill rather than wound. "It's a very
humane way to go," says Mr. Carpenter.
   But the council rejected the idea by a 5-2 vote. Members
said that the plan sounded extreme and that there might be
better ways to control the population.
   Like contraception. Animal-rights representatives argued
at the council meeting that Columbus should consider wildlife
birth control, which entails putting chemicals into animal
food.
   "In the case of nuisance animals, man's first solution is
`let's kill it,'" says Robin Russell, director of Protect Our
Earth Treasures, an animal-rights group. "But if you use
birth control, after a couple of years, you've eradicated the
problem."
</TEXT>
