WSJ900606-0087
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900606-0087.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Paramount Profit
   Skidded by 67%
   In Second Quarter
   ----
   By Robert Daniels
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   PCI
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Paramount Communications Inc. reported a 67%
drop in fiscal second-quarter net income, but the
entertainment company reversed its year-earlier loss from
continuing operations.
   Operating earnings from the entertainment sector dropped
about 13% from a year ago, reflecting write-offs on films,
particularly "Crazy People." And Paramount's publishing
lines, reflecting their seasonal nature, posted slightly
wider operating losses.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But analysts and investors also are looking to what they
expect will be a strong summer film schedule for Paramount.
And the company reiterated its fiscal 1990 profit forecast of
$2.10 to $2.60 a share.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Paramount shares closed at $49.75, up 62.5 cents.
   Net income for the second quarter ended April 30 fell to
$21.2 million, or 18 cents a share, from $65.6 million, or 55
cents a share, in the year-earlier period.
   The latest quarter includes no discontinued operations.
The year-ago quarter reflected a loss of $5.3 million, or
five cents a share, from continuing operations plus $70.9
million, or 60 cents a share, of profit from discontinued
operations.
   Revenue rose 16% to $811.5 million from $699.1 million.
   The latest period includes $21.8 million of interest
income primarily from investment of proceeds from the October
1989 sale of the Associates finance unit to Ford Motor Co.
for $3.35 billion.
   Paramount's "entertainment area has been a little cold
since `Indiana Jones' and except for `The Hunt for Red
October,'" said Alan Kassan, analyst at Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   "But their summer schedule looks like it has a couple of
breakout films. `Another 48 Hours' should do very well {and}
`Days of Thunder' could be big, so I think you'll see more
positive earnings momentum in the second half."
   Paramount estimates operating profit from entertainment at
between $200 million and $250 million for fiscal 1990
compared with $252.2 million in fiscal 1989.
   Paramount's publishing lines reported their operating loss
widened to $27.4 million from $25.8 million. The
educational-publishing business reports the majority of its
sales in the fiscal third and fourth quarters, heading toward
the beginning of the school year.
   For fiscal 1990, Paramount expects publishing-operations
profit of $150 million to $175 million. Fiscal 1989 profit
here was $1.6 million, reflecting a $140 million charge.
   Paramount reported fiscal six-month net income fell 69% to
$42.4 million, or 35 cents a share, from $134.8 million, or
$1.13 a share, a year earlier. The year-earlier period,
however, reflects earnings from discontinued lines of $128.4
million, or $1.08 a share. Revenue advanced 12% to $1.66
billion from $1.47 billion.
</TEXT>
