<HL>
   Regency Cruises Sees
   Loss on Operations
   In the Second Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
06/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS SHIP
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Regency Cruises Inc. said it expects to report
a second-quarter operating loss, reflecting unrest in Latin
America, bad Caribbean weather and a ship that ran aground
last month.
   William Schanz, the company's chairman, disclosed the
expected loss at the company's annual meeting, but didn't
provide further details, including whether Regency will
report a net loss.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   He did say that Regency's cruise business off the coast of
Alaska is "currently booked at approximately 85% of
capacity." Most of that business is done in the third
quarter, which a spokesman said is traditionally the
company's best period.
   A second-quarter loss would be Regency's third consecutive
quarterly deficit. In the first quarter, Regency had a loss
of $2 million, or nine cents a share; in last year's fourth
period, the company had a loss of $1.2 million, or five cents
a share.
   The company pegged its first-quarter and second-quarter
woes to a lack of tour interest in Panama, prior to and
following the U.S. invasion; a State Department advisory that
Americans steer clear of Colombia; and Hurricane Hugo, which
devastated the Caribbean.
   Last month, an electrical snafu forced one of Regency's
three ships, the Regent Star, to run aground in Delaware Bay.
The company subsequently canceled a five-day cruise, and
scratched a two-day cruise because of a small fire on the
ship three days later.
   But a spokesman said things could improve by the third
quarter because Alaska cruise bookings are strong. And
Regency has pulled out of the problem-plagued Caribbean,
opting instead for a potentially more lucrative New
York-Montreal route.
   Meanwhile, holders at the meeting approved adoption of a
stock-option incentive plan for executives that calls for the
issuance of one million new common shares. Holders also
re-elected three directors to three-year terms, including Mr.
Schanz, Fred A. Mayer and Roland J. Hawkins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
